Item.Title: Donkerhoek
Item.Author: AFRICA\graham.dalbock
Item.access_procedure:
Summary of Access Rules and Procedures to Rietfontein repeat site ( Donker hoek)
Site owners will only authorise site access where it is considered safe to do so, based on the known hazards and risks. All known hazard and risk information will be included in the appropriate site permit document. All activities undertaken by visitors to sites must at all times be consistent with the provisions of the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974 (including any amendment, alterations, and additions thereto) and other relevant safety and environmental legislation.
All visitors must conform to the relevant parts of the site owner’s policies. When permission is granted to access a site, it is the responsibility of all visitors to plan the visit and work activity to take into account all hazards associated with access to radio sites. Organisations visiting sites are responsible for ensuring that their staff comply with the site owner’s requirements, rules and procedures at all times and that there is adequate first aid and welfare provision available on site.
Access rules and procedures will generally include the following requirements:
1. All companies working on sites must be accredited by the site owner, either by gaining advanced
accreditation or on a per occasion basis. Unless working within an equipment cabin at ground level all individuals must likewise be accredited. All access will be scheduled with a 4 to 5 hour prior notice on maintenance work.
2. All access must be approved before it takes place.
3. All relevant safety policies set out by the site owner must be adhered to.
4. All persons entering a site must have immediate access to the Access Authorisation covering their visit.
5. The Access Conditions listed on the Access Authorisation must be strictly observed. The work to be
undertaken must be planned to take account of the specific risks listed on the Access Authorisation.
6. Any unexpected visitor to site, or other works being undertaken, that have not been pre- authorised must be reported.
7. Any accidents, near misses/incidents on site must be reported.

Trading as Information and Communications Technology Solutions (ICTS)

E-mail: ronnie@ict-s.co.za

￼￼￼8. Suitable Personal Protective Equipment must be worn at all times taking into account the site specific requirements and activities being undertaken.
9. Only persons specifically listed on an access authorisation can enter a site (except for Ground Cabin access where anyone employed by the accredited access company can enter the site).
10. All site visitors must behave in an orderly manner at all times and be courteous to site providers and neighbours.
11. Site visitors must immediately remove from site all materials arising from their work.
12. RF monitors approved by the site owner must be worn by all climbers at all times. There must be a minimum of one RF monitor per roof top team.
13. Security passes/swipe cards must only be used by those to whom they have been issued. 14. Works to be undertaken must be accurately described in the access authorisation.
15. Non compliance with the Access Rules and Procedures may result in the loss of accreditation of the company, individual or both, or other restrictions on access being approved.
16. Sites are only to be accessed for the purpose detailed in the job description of the access authorisation.
17. Supporting documentation must be provided/available as required. Guidance on what is required must be sought from the site owner.

Access to the site 
o General Access:
Any access should be requested by Authorised personnel, 24 hours in advance to the allocated Service Manager via e-mail with the BCRS Security Officer on copy.
Requesting urgent access for emergencies authorised personnel are allowed to phone the Service Manager and send a follow up e-mail, this will enable the fast tracking of the internal approval process, and avoid any delays. Formal approvals are obtained by the authorised IBM personnel for specific areas in the DC. Security will prepare access cards for each person, and it will be ready for collection at your arrival. The cards will enable access at allocated areas only. All personnel will be required to sign in at reception for access to the premises and the collection of the access card.
o Permanent Access:
Customer to provide list of personnel that will require Permanent Access.
Each person need to provide a Copy of their SA ID or Passport / Electronic Colour ID photo with white back ground and complete the Permanent Access form.
IBM will create permanent Access Cards and these access cards remain on site.
Members with permanent access do not require pre-authorisation, but a courtesy email to notify
IBM of the visit are requested.
All personnel will be required to sign in at reception for access to the premises and the collection of
the access card.
o Permanent Access Validation:
Quarterly Employee Verification & Continuous Business Need for Permanent access members are performed
Validation by Customer Authorised Personnel will be requested on a quarterly basis.
